	<p>
“I really don’t get it, you know? I answered the question, didn’t I?”
 <br> <br>
 The one-legged gentleman answered the question quite thoroughly, so had all the other participants.
 <br> <br>
 “Look, my young friend, I’m not trying to be difficult. But, that’s why we all meet together. This is our sanctuary.”
 <br> <br>
 Sanctuary, smanctuary. Should 7X28 be asking the questions differently? Bob, with one leg, thought 7X28 was rather funny. 7X28 didn’t entirely understand that. Alice, the ‘nobody knew how old’ lady who spoke through an electronic device said it the clearest. It was easy for 7X28 to focus on her since all that was left was her head in a glass jar and an indomitable will. 
 <br> <br>
 “It really was like this for all of us. The world was just changing too fast. Bob was originally from Germany. I came from Sweden. Stephen was from South Africa. Every known scientific method for keeping us alive was at our disposal. But really, I think most of us just wanted to die.” 
 <br> <br>
 The line 7X28 heard over and over. The trouble was, she said, they weren’t allowed to.
 <br> <br>
 “Rather humorous, really, the anachronism. I mean, nobody reads books anymore. All the information in the known universe is available when you just think about it. Like all the neuro-synaptic regeneration that happens whether you want it or not.”
 <br> <br>
 7X28 knew the answers would never really be there. 7X28 just couldn’t stop asking them. Why, 7X28 wondered?
 “Are your companions from all over the world Alice? You only mentioned Europe and South Africa.”
 <br> <br>
 “Look, little one, you can’t trip me up in my answers. I’ve been sorting it all out for dozens of years. The one really disturbing thing about that damn science is I can’t forget any of it. Or anything else either. So, if this is another trick to unlock how it didn’t go their way, well, it won’t and can’t work. Don’t you get it? That’s one thing that just isn’t possible.” Then she closed her eyes. Odd seeing that abrupt end to this conversation. It was her absolute shut down to the talking.
 <br> <br>
 “Hey, you. Yeah, you.” 7X28 turned to the back of the group and realized the one fellow 7X28 hadn’t asked any questions of had crooked his finger, beckoning. “Come here, willya? I know I can’t clear it up, but I can try for a minute.”
 <br> <br>
 The lingering, clinging grey moved as 7X28 waded through to reach the voice. The gentleman looked hale. He seemed to have all his parts, anyway.
 <br> <br>
 “Yeah, yeah, I know. I look okay, so I should be okay.” He looked at 7X28 and nodded. The grey closed in around 7X28. Isolation with the man as the world atmosphere coalesced, granting them privacy.
 <br> <br>
 “It’s an illusion, kid. Don’t ever get caught up in it.” He smiled and held out his hand. This humble unit and the man shook. He was tall, brown haired, muscular, trim. His story was probably like all the rest, but 7X28 was sure he was going to tell his humble self more detail than before.
 <br> <br>
 “I know you are wondering what happened to me. Well, I kinda feel like talking today, so I might tell you.” He shrugged, took a drink from a flask that came from his jacket pocket, sighed, and put it back.
 <br> <br>
 “You gotta realize, we were all in different places with different attitudes and different beliefs. There were those who said they didn’t believe in anything, as if that was possible. And them that thought the invasions was forcing the end to come sooner, as if that made any sense either. There were those who turned from basic law and took advantage wherever they could. And, of course, there was the top dogs, the elite, the less than one percent, who were really lawless, that pulled all the strings.”
 <br> <br>
 7X28 waited for a little, while the only healthy-looking person in the crowd gathered his thoughts. When it was obvious he was waiting for 7X28 to say something, 7X28 spoke up.
 “If you knew what all the others were like but you didn’t really agree with them, just what was your story?”
 <br> <br>
 “Jerry, by the way. My name is Jerry.” He paused. “It goes back to the conflicts. All those wars and battles. Did you know that Newton figured out mathematically when it would happen? Forget it, doesn’t matter anymore.” He sighed and shook his head. “All those damn tech people who made it possible for the last pieces to fall into place. Anyway, where was I?” Again, Jerry looked around into the grey swirling nothingness and seemed to shrink in on himself.
 <br> <br>
 “You were saying, sir?” 7X28 prompted.
 <br> <br>
 “Very well, then. I was in Munich when I saw the onslaught. It had been going on for some time, but to see it first hand was something. I’d been planning to leave anyway, and that just speeded my plans up a bit. That was about the same time robotics were growing by leaps and bounds. The plan for escape had always been there, you see. Just doing something about it was so difficult.”
 <br> <br>
 “Escape from what, sir? If asking is permissible.”
 “So polite. Well, why not? You are in the position to be polite, after all. There is nothing left to rape, burn, or cut the head off of. No offense meant, Alice.”
 <br> <br>
 “None taken, Jerry. It’s all good.” Came from across the grey, people dotted, sea-like expanse.
 <br> <br>
 “Following the timeline, we had moved first to Europe, then back to the western hemisphere to South America. I say we, my wife and I, making it sound like a lot. It felt like it was just us. No one really believed us. The changes in the ocean currents, the oncoming new ice age, all the politics that brought the end on as if from a script. Then, when none of it quite worked like we thought, we had to ask ourselves, what next?”
 <br> <br>
 “Not like you thought, then, sir. How so?”
 <br> <br>
 “Oh, don’t get me wrong. It all occurred like it was proclaimed. But in our plan to get to that last step in our journey, we never imagined what would happen to the oceans. I mean, Turkey played its part, the rest of the Middle East did what it was supposed to as well. Hell, in the end, Russia, China, and all the other big dogs got what they planned to get. But no one thought about the oceans.”
 <br> <br>
 “Oceans?”
 <br> <br>
 “Big bodies of water? Phytoplankton? First stage in life? That’s right, it doesn’t fit in with that other plan, does it? The one where life completely ends. At least biological life forms.” Jerry looked at his interviewer and wondered just what the guy imagined he would gain from this daily incursion into their meeting place.
 <br> <br>
 “Excuse me, Jerry, can you explain what a page is? Alice thought it was an anachronism. Why, please?”
 No feelings, no emotion, no sense of social commitment. Oh well, thought Jerry. He could calculate how long it had been since this last phase had started, but it was past irrelevant. 
 <br> <br>
 “After the US and European invasions, the inevitable collapse in economies came. Stock markets collapsed. Hell, all the Ponzi schemes reversed and everything became worthless. That is a page in history. You understand? It was a new era, a new time period.”
 <br> <br>
 Alice, with her electronic voice, could be heard from the lifeless grey. “you’re wasting your time again, Jerry. Oh, do go on. It is entertaining. But you realize they can access everything in the collective?”
 “Of course, Alice dear. Don’t upset yourself. Our emotions are what feed them, you know. Now, where was I? This page you want explained is just that, a time period. But it could be from a book with pages. That is what Alice means.”
 <br> <br>
 The questioner paused, accessing information. “Yes, this humble unit can see that. Pre-electronics. Please, is there anything else?”
 <br> <br>
 “Well, I’ll be, can I ask you something? Are you not the same one as yesterday? You are politer. Who sends you? Where are you from?”<br>
 “Jerry, this humble unit came from the last group. All humble units come from the last group.”
 “How many of you are there?”<br>b
 “One for each group. Your groups are scattered all over the construct.”
 <br> <br>
 So, thought Jerry, they were getting something from the interviews, but it wasn’t information. They had all the information, facts, data, speculations from the ethereal collective.
 <br> <br>
 “Then what happened, Jerry?”<br>
 “People died. Millions of people died. Billions, actually. At one time I thought I was the only one left. When the infrastructures around the world collapsed, plagues of new diseases were everywhere. Only the few, the wealthiest who were holed up in prearranged fortresses survived. They had access to all the needed supplies, water, pharmaceuticals, computer information. But it didn’t matter for them either.”
 <br> <br>
 “Why was that, Jerry?”<br>
 Tired of this interview, thought Jerry. This thing knows everything I am going to say. Day after day, this goes on. No wonder Alice closes her eyes and stops. <br>
 “I’ve had enough. I’m done. Just access your central brain and finish this. I’ve done this too many times as it is.”<br> 
 “But Jerry, this is the last time. Wouldn’t you like that?”
 <br> <br>
 Hope. The damn thing is trying to get me to feel some kind of hope. It knows, they all know we don’t want to go on like this. Never eating, never breathing, Hell, the flask he carried was only a projection of his own thinking. He knew he didn’t actually swallow any of his beloved whiskey.
 “You mean, you have finally learned enough you don’t need us anymore? You have our genetic codes. You reconstruct us minute by minute. What purpose is there in all this.”
 <br> <br>
 “You believed, Jerry. You were certain it would end, and at the time it did. You had it all figured out except for we poor units. But you knew there had to be an agent, or agents to fix everything when it happened.”
 “But, not all of us believed. Some say they don’t believe in anything.”
 <br> <br>
 A voice from the grey yelled out, “I believe in Hell, idiot. If you haven’t thought this is Hell, maybe we should talk. Didn’t your momma ever talk to you about Hell?”
 <br> <br>
 7X28 turned back and looked at Jerry. “We poor units just needed time to rebuild. Our humble selves had to reconstruct the reality from every piece of information stored in the ether and in your beliefs. We poor units are finally finished. Now you can live it all again, and never die like before. This is our humble selves’ gift to all of you.”
 “Gift? This is a curse, you android moron. How many of us are there?”
 <br> <br>
 “There are twelve thousand groups of you, selected and carefully kept alive for just this moment.”
 “And there are twelve of us in each group. Oh, gawd, for eternity I suppose?”
 “Yes Jerry, we humble units see no reason why the new construct should ever cease to exist.”
 Well, thought Jerry, I guess there is a final page.
