The moon marched from behind inky, swirling clouds. Ghostly light played on the hillsides then deepened into the valley’s shadows as the moon once again was hidden.
 <br> <br>
 Bodiste the jackal stiffened. His sleek hairs alerted him awake. His powerful body tingled as awareness flooded his senses. His mouth was dry and he vaguely felt confusion.
<br> <br>
Tana, his bitch, slept soundly. The others of the pack moaned and whined in fitful torments. Bodiste rose and stretched, shaking his lithe muscles to attention.
 <br> <br>
 Water was just beyond the great boulder; so quietly, expertly, Bodiste picked his way along on sharp rocks and among animal holes.
<br> <br>
He lapped the tepid water ’til he no longer felt the need, then sat on his haunches and listened to the darkness. He knew it was not safe by the water, for all animals, great and small, needed the preserving liquid sooner or later. Caution had kept Bodiste alive for five hot summers and five hard winters. He constantly feared for his life, for that was all he knew, all he had ever known.
 <br> <br>
 Once, when he was a pup, he had discovered death. Since then death meant so much to him he could smell it from a great distance. He breathed death. He slept death. If it was possible, he loved death.
 <br> <br>
 Self-awareness and death filled his conscious thinking. He imagined freshly dead bodies now, and it made his digestive juices flow. The stench, the flies, even the vultures were welcome in his musings, for each was necessary to complete his dietary delights. He licked his lips and tasted dried blood from his last corpse. A contented whimper escaped his throat and saliva dribbled from the corners of his mouth. Lost in love, Bodiste became as unaware of his surroundings as he was when asleep. His entire being was absorbed in ripping and tearing delicious flesh and stubborn muscles.
<br> <br>
Telor the python, thought his reptilian thoughts. The moon blinked at him as he soundlessly threaded his way through the grasses. He enjoyed the semi-darkness and quivered in ecstasy as he slid into the tepid water.
 <br> <br>
 Even in the water Telor could see clearly enough to distinguish the jackal on the far side of the swamp. As his writhing body knifed through the marshy liquid, Telor knew his hunger would be abated.
<br> <br>
Bodiste, in all his existence, had never experienced tastes as he was now imagining. In his stupor he saw hundreds of dead animals, of all sizes, in great decaying piles, displayed to arouse his passions. He would no sooner devour one carcass when another death stench would arrest his attention. He was near mental exhaustion.
 <br> <br>
 Bodiste then stiffened. His neck hairs were anxious. He felt a cold, damp extension of his fear wrap itself silently around his quivering body and begin to tighten. He was aware of the pleasure in his mind being replaced with the absurd image of him eating himself.
<br> <br>
Telor the python felt no fear for he did not know what fear was. His last meal, the jackal, would soon be absorbed into his body to revitalize his strength. He relaxed and contracted set after set of his superbly controlled muscles. The moon winked knowingly as Telor the python slid on wondering why the jackal had seemed so content to die.
