	<p>
I arrived at the gym a half hour later, having played through all the recollections once again of my time in Japan. I had fallen for everything about the country and culture. It was a time in my young life when I needed that very much. After my parents disappeared, I ran away from the only memories 
of love I could remember.
<br> <br>
The name of the gym was LifeEnergy. It offered the usual assortment of machines that I had no interest in, swimming that I wasn’t fond of either, and an indoor track that I didn’t need since I already ran way too much. I went to LifeEnergy for the knife-throwing range mostly. There was also a small dojo I was fond of, and at this time of night, I didn’t think anyone would be using it. Too bad there wasn’t a shooting range as well, but I guess I couldn’t have everything.
<br> <br>
I liked this gym because no one got too personal. I could work out in spandex or leathers, and no one would bat an eye. Of course, you have to look twice to see me anyway. Most people had a membership, but I chose the option of paying for whatever time I spent there rather than spending money for time when I would probably not show up.
<br> <br>
The woman at the wrap-around check-in counter was a blonde amazon. She was at least six one in low work-out shoes. I was a head and a half taller than the counter, but I still had to look up to speak with her sitting at her desk. She was here the last time I came, so at least I didn’t have to explain why I was out so late.
<br> <br>
That really got old.
<br> <br>
I signed in, Darby Kellehen, and the check-in woman told me that there was a group of men using the throwing arena. Well, I guess you have to take whatever you can get. I was hoping to be alone, but at least this late at night the place wasn’t crawling with people.
<br> <br>
After changing in the locker room and spending twenty minutes warming up, I ghosted my way into the throwing arena. There were five men there in fairly tight-fitting workout clothes. I knew from experience that tighter was better. The arena was moderately sized, perhaps thirty by thirty, with targets of varying sizes placed at different heights on three sides of the room. The group was made up of three tall white guys and two-average sized Easterners, Chinese from their appearance and demeanor. The Eastern men were advising the white guys on knife-throwing form: how to stand, the aim, follow through and preparation for the next throw. It looked like they were demonstrating martial arts competition exercises. I watched for a few minutes before they noticed I was there.
<br> <br>
One of the tall guys came over to me and asked, “Are you here to practice? I don’t remember seeing you for any of the knife-throwing lessons.” He was polite, but he looked at me like I must be mistaken and in the wrong place.
<br> <br>
Why is it that everyone thinks I am either confused or mistaken because of my appearance? Is this sizism?
<br> <br>
“I don’t come here often, but I really like the arena. It reminds me of where I learned to throw.” I thought again of Japan and where I studied for four years to perfect blade handling. “I won’t take much time; I’ve already warmed up and all I need to do is final preparations and fully realize my reason for engaging.” I checked out the men who were still standing together looking me over. I probably looked like Pippi Longstocking to them with my red hair in tails that acted like they had a life of their own. However, my large green eyes and pale skin were more fit to an Anime battle figure.
<br> <br>
The man who talked to me politely asked his companions if they minded resting for a while so this young lady could go through her routine. They moved back. I am sure their curiosity was aroused. I strapped on my gear and stretched into it. I chose to wear leathers and go barefoot. For this workout I had chosen a back harness and leg harnesses each with three knives. With a heavier knife strapped to each forearm, I had eleven weapons in all.
<br> <br>
I could hear some comments and some soft chuckling from the Eastern men. I swung my arms and kicked to get the fit, and then I relaxed into a heisoku dachi, relaxed bow, and breathed deeply.
<br> <br>
I could still hear chuckling. Since I had endured this type of belittling behavior, especially from men, all my life, I ignored it and just did my thing.
<br> <br>
Once up from the heisoku dachi, I smoothly executed a back flip, followed by a twist and handless cartwheel. I straightened and ran quickly toward the far wall doing a succession of forward flips. The forth flip was higher with an extra lateral twist in the air and right arm release. I followed this routine with slight variations around the three walls with targets, releasing knives from one leg or the other, over my shoulder or from the forearm. Finally, I completed my attack with a series of floor, leg, and hand sweeps whose purpose was to disarm and disable anyone left after I had eleven opponents down.
<br> <br>
Upon surveying the battle field, I then stood, took a deep breath and once again bowed to the wall, my opponent. From start to finish, my attack and finale took less than forty seconds. Adrenaline still thrummed through my veins.
<br> <br>
It defined me.
<br> <br>
I remained in the proper position of respect for my fallen opponent for the count of ten. I took another deep cleansing breath and prepared to leave. My muscles were loose, and I felt my balance was once again in place. Knife throwing, when done properly, is second only to swimming for using all the body’s muscles.
<br> <br>
The five men who were watching did not chuckle as I walked the arena pulling all my knives from the various targets. Some of the targets were above my reach, and I was forced to climb to retrieve my weapon. Once I had all the knives sheathed again, I thought about my chances for survival.
<br> <br>
Out of eleven knife throws, six were within the bull’s eye, the center of the heart, three were within the equivalent of major heart arteries, and the other two were still within three inches of the heart’s center. All had been thrown on the run, during forward or backward flips or while spinning. Except for a slight hesitation on the last knife from my back harness, one thrown while twisting in the air, both feet up, head down and turning to focus on the next target, all of the knives were delivered within three seconds of each other. I knew the one extra second of hesitation on that individual throw could mean my death.
<br> <br>
“Chīsana senshi, you just died.” “Thank you, honorable sensei; I will try most sincerely not to die next time.” It was a ritual conversation that I needed to keep my perspective. It reinforced boundaries for my passion.
<br> <br>
I turned and walked to the arena entrance. My flaming red hair was bound in a succession of bands, then twisted in a loop and pinned. My slight form was anything but imposing. I did not breathe hard, and I was only moderately flushed. However, from experience I knew my emerald green eyes were expanded to twice normal size. As I approached the entrance, the two Eastern men bowed and kept their eyes on the ground. The three large white guys saw this and followed suit. I did not look back, nor did I think about their attitude again as I silently padded out of the throwing arena.
<br> <br>
The dojo, a separate large room on the other side of the gym, was empty. Even though the gym was new by most standards, those who had used this dojo had already imprinted a feeling of love and dedication on the walls and in the floor. I found a small mat against one wall and placed it on the floor facing the entrance. I folded down on the mat in a full lotus and began breathing slow calming breaths. Once I had descended, far enough down to feel each individual beat of my heart, like the slow beat in a drum circle, like the slow speaking of trees to each other; I slipped into my primary form of real rest. Connections formed and I honored my parents and sensei in centering. When I felt my eyes begin to move back and forth in a regular pattern, I dropped out of the drum circle and into quiet, hopefully dreamless, sleep.
