Texas, especially Austin, is a poseur. When I leave my son’s gentrified apartment, the chilly 28 degrees is a faint reminder of the farm in winter. But only the cold. And the cold is only a shock because it is so dramatically different from Medellin. How have the dreams turned to such an altered reality? 
 <br> <br>
 However, it is the snow that gets attention. The fascination of fluffy white stuff drifting through the inky blue skies makes residents from almost anywhere slow down and think. Why? What is it about the wonder of snow that reminds us of childhood? Or am I reminiscing about something that few people remember anymore?
 <br> <br>
 Sledding with siblings, bonfires where hot chocolate and s’mores wait at the bottom of Webb Ridge Grade, ice in the eyebrows, and air so cold it is glacial just to breathe. Then hook the sleds to the rear bumper of the old station wagon and get pulled to the top of the hill for another go.
 <br> <br>
 I suppose, it could just be the Mandela Effect. I find that many of my memories come into question by those who have never experienced Northern Idaho, or life in the country, or in a belief that seasons will resolve themselves. . . like the way we all expect economic lows to resolve themselves before bottoms, so to speak, drop out. It is a thought fringed with barren truth. When technical diagrams are superimposed on visual actualities.
 <br> <br>
 Texans, however, for the most part, don’t like the cold or snow. I can understand this. They drive like the roads are an asylum, and the lunatics are in charge. When it snows, and the roads are slick with ice, they Zamboni to work. The morning commute is a test of confidence, not only in their knowledge of physics, but in their connection to the past, the collective memories of ancestors who hazarded adverse weather and conquered.
 <br> <br>
 So, hold fast to the entrapping of growth, Austin. To the magnetic attraction of insufficient infrastructure, dotted with an increase of downtrodden who cannot weather snow, who dream of hot chocolate and s’mores and any other comfort that would relieve their plight. Stay focused?
 <br> <br>
 To know what that is, shouldn’t there be a better understanding of where the Austin Phenomenon came from? Some experience success, some encounter disappointment, some undergo shock. A snow quietly reflects inner ideas and expectations of those affected. The cold defines the limited resources of a city unprepared for either too many people — too fast to cope — or the truth of a reverse migration. As in the Dust Bowl Days, thousands of citizens — wracked with despair, in need of hope — march steadily to Austin, away from where there was once opportunity and toward a dream. 
